data.name: UseDefaults.Text
data.value: Use default settings to create a Virtual Mac

data.name: NewDescription2.Text
data.value: This option guides you throught the basic configurations neccesary for creating a new Virtual Macintosh Machine.

data.name: UseDefaultsDescription2.Text
data.value: You can automatically create a .mcc file with default settings. The resulting virtual machine will not have a virtual hard disk associated with it, so you will have to select one using the Settings dialog.

data.name: AddExistDescription2.Text
data.value: You can add a Virtual Macintosh Machine to the Virtual Mac Console from existing .mcc files.

data.name: RAMDescription.Text
data.value: Set the RAM for this Macintosh:

data.name: RAMHelpTitle.Text
data.value: Allocate RAM for this Mac by:

data.name: RAMHelp.Text
data.value: To improve the performance of this Mac and to run more applications on its operating system, increase the amount of RAM allocated to it. To leave more RAM for other virtual machines on your system, use the recommended RAM allocation.

data.name: ActionDescription.Text
data.value: You can create a new Virtual Mac or add an existing one to the Virtual Mac Console.

data.name: Help4.Text
data.value: Selecting an Operating System here allows the wizard to reccomend appropiate settings for this Virtual Macintosh. If the desired guest Operating System is not listed, select an operating system that requires an equivalent amount of memory or select Other.

data.name: WarningLowerSize.Text
data.value: Please enter a size value between 4 MB and 130,557 MB.

data.name: VDInfoAboutVD.Text
data.value: To learn more about virtual disks, see Virtual Mac Help. For advanced virtual hard disk options, use the Virtual Disk Wizard.

data.name: NewVDHelp.Text
data.value: Type a name for the new virtual hard disk. Unless you specify a different location, the virtual hard disk file will automatically be saved in the same location as the virtual macintosh configuration file.

data.name: NewMac60Help.Text
data.value: A virtual hard disk is a .dsk file that is stored on your physical hard disk and is used to contain the guest operating system, applications and data.

data.name: NewMac60About.Text
data.value: The first virtual hard disk you create or select for your virtual machine is called Disk 1 in Settings and is the Startup disk.

data.name: HelpA.Text
data.value: Specify the .mcc file you want to add to the Virtual Mac Console.

data.name: HelpC.Text
data.value: Type the name for the Virtual Macintosh file. Choose a name that will help you identify this Virtual Mac's hardware or software configuration or which operating system it will run. The file is automatically saved to the 'My Macs' folder. To save it to a different location, use the Browse button.

data.name: OpenSettingsAfterFinish.Text
data.value: When I click Finish, open Settings.

data.name: AdviceClickFinish.Text
data.value: To close this wizard, click Finish.

data.name: AdviceNoHD.Text
data.value: Before you can install an operating system on this Virtual Mac, you must add a virtual hard disk to it.

data.name: DescriptionEnd.Text
data.value: You have completed succefully the New Virtual Mac Wizard and have named your Mac:

data.name: TitleEnd.Text
data.value: Completing the New Virtual Mac Wizard

data.name: TitleStart.Text
data.value: Welcome to the New Virtual Macintosh Wizard

data.name: DescriptionStart.Text
data.value: This wizard helps you create and configure a new Virtual Macintosh or add an existing Virtual Macintosh to the Virtual Mac Console. The Virtual Macintosh configuration is stored in a .mcc file. To continue, click Next.
